<span class="anchor" id="line-202"></span><span class="anchor" id="line-203"></span><ul><li style="list-style-type:none"><p class="line862">See this link: <a class="https" href="https://askubuntu.com/questions/1190764/why-doesnt-a-bootable-usb-boot/">Why Doesn't a Bootable USB Boot</a> <span class="anchor" id="line-204"></span><span class="anchor" id="line-205"></span></li></ul><div><table><tbody><tr>  <td style="background-color: #CCFF99"><p class="line862"> There are more details at the sub-page <strong><a href="/community/Installation/FromUSBStick/bootUSB">/bootUSB</a></strong> </td>
</tr>
</tbody></table></div><span class="anchor" id="line-206"></span><span class="anchor" id="line-207"></span><span class="anchor" id="line-208"></span><p class="line867">
<h1 id="Known_Issues">Known Issues</h1>
<span class="anchor" id="line-209"></span><span class="anchor" id="line-210"></span><ul><li><p class="line862">There are problems with the versions of the Startup Disk Creator alias usb-creator in versions of Ubuntu older than 16.04 LTS. There are similar problems with old versions of Unetbootin. Until these problems are solved other tools work, for example <strong>mkusb</strong> and <strong>Win32DiskImager</strong> described in the following links, <a class="https" href="https://help.ubuntu.com/community/mkusb">https://help.ubuntu.com/community/mkusb</a> and <a class="https" href="https://wiki.ubuntu.com/Win32DiskImager/iso2usb">https://wiki.ubuntu.com/Win32DiskImager/iso2usb</a> <span class="anchor" id="line-211"></span><span class="anchor" id="line-212"></span></li><li class="gap"><p class="line862">The version 0.3.2 (and newer versions) of the Startup Disk Creator alias usb-creator in Ubuntu 16.04 LTS (and newer versions) <strong>clones</strong> the iso file and creates a read-only file system. This method is very robust, but <strong>if you want to re-use the USB stick as a storage drive, you must restore it</strong>. Two methods are described in the next paragraph. <span class="anchor" id="line-213"></span><span class="anchor" id="line-214"></span></li></ul><p class="line867">
<h1 id="Postrequisites_-_restore_the_USB_stick">Postrequisites - restore the USB stick</h1>
<span class="anchor" id="line-215"></span><span class="anchor" id="line-216"></span><p class="line874">'Postrequisites' - after installation: how to restore the USB stick to a standard storage drive. The standard is an MSDOS partition table (MBR) and a partition with the FAT32 file system. <span class="anchor" id="line-217"></span><span class="anchor" id="line-218"></span><p class="line867">
